{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_012hz85pw5WxEZJKUb2PKyHV","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→<html>\n     2→<body>\n     3→  <p>Jakarta Persistence implementations of the repository interfaces. This\n     4→    is part of the infrastructure.</p>\n     5→</body>\n     6→</html>\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01CeohoG4JHS9obNcGYJWBuV","session_id":"cb64f649-59c6-4f3a-a73b-f24ff02d923c","uuid":"2dcb262a-48a6-4240-a45a-3755feeb6774"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01JAWf2hNxiBh11MeBPvxrFu","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→<html>\n     2→<body>\n     3→  <p>DTOs for the booking client facade.</p>\n     4→  <p>DTOs are designed in a use case-driven fashion, closely related to the\n     5→    service layer interface. They represent a particular section of the domain\n     6→    model, which may cross aggregate boundaries. They have no business logic and\n     7→    are immutable.</p>\n     8→  <p>The reason for using DTOs is mainly to loosen the coupling of the\n     9→    application and the user interface. It allows us to build the domain model\n    10→    completely without having to conforming to any UI-related conventions or\n    11→    requirements, such as JavaBean getter methods or no-args constructors. We\n    12→    also avoid exposing functionality that is internal to the domain model to\n    13→    the UI layer.</p>\n    14→  <p>Furthermore, we have a clear contract for what part of the object graph\n    15→    is loaded from the database when the service layer call returns. If domain\n    16→    model objects are passed on to the UI layer, it will be necessary to keep\n    17→    the database access window (e.g. the Hibernate session) open during the\n    18→    entire processing of the view (the Open Session In View pattern), otherwise\n    19→    an uninitialized part of the model could accidentally be accessed, causing\n    20→    an error. For example, if the UI layer were to receive a Cargo instance,\n    21→    that could be navigated to access the Itinerary, iterate over the Legs of\n    22→    the itinerary, access the Leg's CarrierMovement and then the\n    23→    CarrierMovement's Location and so on. In addition to effectively tying the\n    24→    UI layer and the rest of the application to the same JVM, letting the UI\n    25→    layer decide when to initialize data may be very inefficient. DTOs are a\n    26→    natural way of loading only the relevant data for a particular use case, and\n    27→    blocking access to the rest.</p>\n    28→  <p>Using DTOs also makes the service layer reusable across different kinds\n    29→    of front-ends: web, rich clients, other back-end systems etc. Remember that\n    30→    classes that are persisted with Hibernate or similar technologies are\n    31→    modified in runtime, so that for example collection-valued fields are\n    32→    swapped for customized implementations that allow lazy loading. If these\n    33→    persisted domain model classes are to be de-serialized in another JVM, those\n    34→    O/R-mapping-specific classes need to be available there as well, which is\n    35→    not very elegant.</p>\n    36→  <p>A caveat to consider: The usefulness of DTOs may vary with the degree\n    37→    of vertical separation in the application. If it's very unlikely that your\n    38→    application will use anything other than a web interface, and that it\n    39→    otherwise are no problems running the web layer together with the rest of\n    40→    the application, you may want to avoid the overhead of maintaining several\n    41→    similar sets of classes.</p>\n    42→</body>\n    43→</html>\n    44→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01CeohoG4JHS9obNcGYJWBuV","session_id":"cb64f649-59c6-4f3a-a73b-f24ff02d923c","uuid":"1186e32c-01e7-4bc8-9d73-24d590e6f140"}
