{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_019exeyHpGpfsw3u7vLxUfMZ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.web;\n     2→\n     3→import static java.util.stream.Collectors.toList;\n     4→\n     5→import java.util.List;\n     6→import javax.annotation.PostConstruct;\n     7→import javax.enterprise.context.RequestScoped;\n     8→import javax.inject.Inject;\n     9→import javax.inject.Named;\n    10→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.BookingServiceFacade;\n    11→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.dto.CargoRoute;\n    12→\n    13→/**\n    14→ * Handles listing cargo. Operates against a dedicated service facade, and could easily be rewritten\n    15→ * as a thick client. Completely separated from the domain layer, unlike the tracking user\n    16→ * interface.\n    17→ *\n    18→ * <p>In order to successfully keep the domain model shielded from user interface considerations,\n    19→ * this approach is generally preferred to the one taken in the tracking controller. However, there\n    20→ * is never any one perfect solution for all situations, so we've chosen to demonstrate two\n    21→ * polarized ways to build user interfaces.\n    22→ */\n    23→@Named\n    24→@RequestScoped\n    25→public class ListCargo {\n    26→\n    27→  @Inject private BookingServiceFacade bookingServiceFacade;\n    28→\n    29→  private List<CargoRoute> notRoutedCargos;\n    30→  private List<CargoRoute> routedUnclaimedCargos;\n    31→  private List<CargoRoute> claimedCargos;\n    32→\n    33→  @PostConstruct\n    34→  public void init() {\n    35→    List<CargoRoute> cargos = bookingServiceFacade.listAllCargos();\n    36→    notRoutedCargos = cargos.stream().filter(route -> !route.isRouted()).collect(toList());\n    37→    routedUnclaimedCargos =\n    38→        cargos.stream().filter(route -> route.isRouted() && !route.isClaimed()).collect(toList());\n    39→    claimedCargos = cargos.stream().filter(CargoRoute::isClaimed).collect(toList());\n    40→  }\n    41→\n    42→  public List<CargoRoute> getNotRoutedCargos() {\n    43→    return notRoutedCargos;\n    44→  }\n    45→\n    46→  public List<CargoRoute> getRoutedUnclaimedCargos() {\n    47→    return routedUnclaimedCargos;\n    48→  }\n    49→\n    50→  public List<CargoRoute> getClaimedCargos() {\n    51→    return claimedCargos;\n    52→  }\n    53→}\n    54→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01P9o4BPvGfqGgpY4qAiCPkX","session_id":"cb64f649-59c6-4f3a-a73b-f24ff02d923c","uuid":"700aa169-bb5c-4c44-bc10-fbe61eb28259"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ADWimADEGnUrBx4sacAEbj","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.web;\n     2→\n     3→import javax.enterprise.context.RequestScoped;\n     4→import javax.inject.Inject;\n     5→import javax.inject.Named;\n     6→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.BookingServiceFacade;\n     7→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.dto.CargoRoute;\n     8→\n     9→/**\n    10→ * Handles viewing cargo details. Operates against a dedicated service facade, and could easily be\n    11→ * rewritten as a thick Swing client. Completely separated from the domain layer, unlike the\n    12→ * tracking user interface.\n    13→ *\n    14→ * <p>In order to successfully keep the domain model shielded from user interface considerations,\n    15→ * this approach is generally preferred to the one taken in the tracking controller. However, there\n    16→ * is never any one perfect solution for all situations, so we've chosen to demonstrate two\n    17→ * polarized ways to build user interfaces.\n    18→ */\n    19→@Named\n    20→@RequestScoped\n    21→public class CargoDetails {\n    22→\n    23→  @Inject private BookingServiceFacade bookingServiceFacade;\n    24→\n    25→  private String trackingId;\n    26→  private CargoRoute cargo;\n    27→\n    28→  public String getTrackingId() {\n    29→    return trackingId;\n    30→  }\n    31→\n    32→  public void setTrackingId(String trackingId) {\n    33→    this.trackingId = trackingId;\n    34→  }\n    35→\n    36→  public CargoRoute getCargo() {\n    37→    return cargo;\n    38→  }\n    39→\n    40→  public void load() {\n    41→    cargo = bookingServiceFacade.loadCargoForRouting(trackingId);\n    42→  }\n    43→}\n    44→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01P9o4BPvGfqGgpY4qAiCPkX","session_id":"cb64f649-59c6-4f3a-a73b-f24ff02d923c","uuid":"8d6afb99-46ef-4aab-b81c-542286c6954b"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_018Ksz8xTmCjVyGhCpLycBtA","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.web;\n     2→\n     3→import java.io.Serializable;\n     4→import java.util.List;\n     5→import javax.annotation.PostConstruct;\n     6→import javax.faces.view.ViewScoped;\n     7→import javax.inject.Inject;\n     8→import javax.inject.Named;\n     9→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.BookingServiceFacade;\n    10→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.dto.CargoStatus;\n    11→\n    12→/**\n    13→ * Handles tracking cargo. Operates against a dedicated service facade, and could easily be\n    14→ * rewritten as a thick Swing client. Completely separated from the domain layer, unlike the public\n    15→ * tracking user interface.\n    16→ *\n    17→ * <p>In order to successfully keep the domain model shielded from user interface considerations,\n    18→ * this approach is generally preferred to the one taken in the public tracking controller. However,\n    19→ * there is never any one perfect solution for all situations, so we've chosen to demonstrate two\n    20→ * polarized ways to build user interfaces.\n    21→ */\n    22→@Named(\"admin.track\")\n    23→@ViewScoped\n    24→public class Track implements Serializable {\n    25→\n    26→  private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;\n    27→\n    28→  @Inject private BookingServiceFacade bookingServiceFacade;\n    29→\n    30→  private List<String> trackingIds;\n    31→  private String trackingId;\n    32→  private CargoStatus cargo;\n    33→\n    34→  public List<String> getTrackingIds(String query) {\n    35→    return trackingIds;\n    36→  }\n    37→\n    38→  public String getTrackingId() {\n    39→    return trackingId;\n    40→  }\n    41→\n    42→  public void setTrackingId(String trackingId) {\n    43→    this.trackingId = trackingId;\n    44→  }\n    45→\n    46→  public CargoStatus getCargo() {\n    47→    return this.cargo;\n    48→  }\n    49→\n    50→  @PostConstruct\n    51→  public void init() {\n    52→    trackingIds = bookingServiceFacade.listAllTrackingIds();\n    53→  }\n    54→\n    55→  public void onTrackById() {\n    56→    cargo = bookingServiceFacade.loadCargoForTracking(this.trackingId);\n    57→  }\n    58→}\n    59→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01P9o4BPvGfqGgpY4qAiCPkX","session_id":"cb64f649-59c6-4f3a-a73b-f24ff02d923c","uuid":"4ed288d6-4641-4205-9345-de1c0d49c47e"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01K6HjAb6xExx2iua5MaFdsc","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.web;\n     2→\n     3→import java.io.Serializable;\n     4→import java.time.LocalDate;\n     5→import java.time.temporal.ChronoUnit;\n     6→import java.util.ArrayList;\n     7→import java.util.List;\n     8→import javax.annotation.PostConstruct;\n     9→import javax.faces.application.FacesMessage;\n    10→import javax.faces.context.FacesContext;\n    11→import javax.faces.flow.FlowScoped;\n    12→import javax.inject.Inject;\n    13→import javax.inject.Named;\n    14→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.BookingServiceFacade;\n    15→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.dto.Location;\n    16→import org.primefaces.PrimeFaces;\n    17→\n    18→/**\n    19→ * Handles booking cargo. Operates against a dedicated service facade, and could easily be rewritten\n    20→ * as a thick client. Completely separated from the domain layer, unlike the tracking user\n    21→ * interface.\n    22→ *\n    23→ * <p>In order to successfully keep the domain model shielded from user interface considerations,\n    24→ * this approach is generally preferred to the one taken in the tracking controller. However, there\n    25→ * is never any one perfect solution for all situations, so we've chosen to demonstrate two\n    26→ * polarized ways to build user interfaces.\n    27→ */\n    28→@Named\n    29→@FlowScoped(\"booking\")\n    30→public class Booking implements Serializable {\n    31→\n    32→  private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;\n    33→\n    34→  private static final long MIN_JOURNEY_DURATION = 1; // Journey should be 1 day minimum.\n    35→\n    36→  @Inject private BookingServiceFacade bookingServiceFacade;\n    37→  @Inject private FacesContext context;\n    38→\n    39→  private LocalDate today = null;\n    40→  private List<Location> locations;\n    41→\n    42→  private String originUnlocode;\n    43→  private String originName;\n    44→  private String destinationName;\n    45→  private String destinationUnlocode;\n    46→  private LocalDate arrivalDeadline;\n    47→\n    48→  private boolean bookable = false;\n    49→  private long duration = -1;\n    50→\n    51→  @PostConstruct\n    52→  public void init() {\n    53→    today = LocalDate.now();\n    54→    locations = bookingServiceFacade.listShippingLocations();\n    55→  }\n    56→\n    57→  public List<Location> getLocations() {\n    58→    List<Location> filteredLocations = new ArrayList<>();\n    59→    String locationToRemove = null;\n    60→\n    61→    if (context.getViewRoot().getViewId().endsWith(\"destination.xhtml\")) {\n    62→      // In the destination menu, origin can't be selected.\n    63→      locationToRemove = originUnlocode;\n    64→    } else { // Vice-versa.\n    65→      if (destinationUnlocode != null) {\n    66→        locationToRemove = destinationUnlocode;\n    67→      }\n    68→    }\n    69→\n    70→    for (Location location : locations) {\n    71→      if (!location.getUnLocode().equalsIgnoreCase(locationToRemove)) {\n    72→        filteredLocations.add(location);\n    73→      }\n    74→    }\n    75→\n    76→    return filteredLocations;\n    77→  }\n    78→\n    79→  public String getOriginUnlocode() {\n    80→    return originUnlocode;\n    81→  }\n    82→\n    83→  public void setOriginUnlocode(String originUnlocode) {\n    84→    this.originUnlocode = originUnlocode;\n    85→    this.originName =\n    86→        locations\n    87→            .stream()\n    88→            .filter(location -> location.getUnLocode().equalsIgnoreCase(originUnlocode))\n    89→            .findAny()\n    90→            .get()\n    91→            .getName();\n    92→  }\n    93→\n    94→  public String getOriginName() {\n    95→    return originName;\n    96→  }\n    97→\n    98→  public String getDestinationUnlocode() {\n    99→    return destinationUnlocode;\n   100→  }\n   101→\n   102→  public void setDestinationUnlocode(String destinationUnlocode) {\n   103→    this.destinationUnlocode = destinationUnlocode;\n   104→    this.destinationName =\n   105→        locations\n   106→            .stream()\n   107→            .filter(location -> location.getUnLocode().equalsIgnoreCase(destinationUnlocode))\n   108→            .findAny()\n   109→            .get()\n   110→            .getName();\n   111→  }\n   112→\n   113→  public String getDestinationName() {\n   114→    return destinationName;\n   115→  }\n   116→\n   117→  public LocalDate getToday() {\n   118→    return today;\n   119→  }\n   120→\n   121→  public LocalDate getArrivalDeadline() {\n   122→    return arrivalDeadline;\n   123→  }\n   124→\n   125→  public void setArrivalDeadline(LocalDate arrivalDeadline) {\n   126→    this.arrivalDeadline = arrivalDeadline;\n   127→  }\n   128→\n   129→  public long getDuration() {\n   130→    return duration;\n   131→  }\n   132→\n   133→  public boolean isBookable() {\n   134→    return bookable;\n   135→  }\n   136→\n   137→  public void deadlineUpdated() {\n   138→    duration = ChronoUnit.DAYS.between(today, arrivalDeadline);\n   139→\n   140→    if (duration >= MIN_JOURNEY_DURATION) {\n   141→      bookable = true;\n   142→    } else {\n   143→      bookable = false;\n   144→    }\n   145→\n   146→    PrimeFaces.current().ajax().update(\"dateForm:durationPanel\");\n   147→    PrimeFaces.current().ajax().update(\"dateForm:bookBtn\");\n   148→  }\n   149→\n   150→  public String register() {\n   151→    if (!originUnlocode.equals(destinationUnlocode)) {\n   152→      bookingServiceFacade.bookNewCargo(originUnlocode, destinationUnlocode, arrivalDeadline);\n   153→    } else {\n   154→      // UI now prevents from selecting same origin/destination\n   155→      FacesMessage message = new FacesMessage(\"Origin and destination cannot be the same.\");\n   156→      message.setSeverity(FacesMessage.SEVERITY_ERROR);\n   157→      context.addMessage(null, message);\n   158→      return null;\n   159→    }\n   160→\n   161→    return \"/admin/dashboard.xhtml\";\n   162→  }\n   163→\n   164→  public String getReturnValue() {\n   165→    return \"/admin/dashboard.xhtml\";\n   166→  }\n   167→}\n   168→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01P9o4BPvGfqGgpY4qAiCPkX","session_id":"cb64f649-59c6-4f3a-a73b-f24ff02d923c","uuid":"f534b0a2-f5f1-4706-a758-9695244ed1ce"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Ag3WrtkvF2ecGLHzQoFP4n","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.web;\n     2→\n     3→import java.io.Serializable;\n     4→import java.util.List;\n     5→import javax.faces.view.ViewScoped;\n     6→import javax.inject.Inject;\n     7→import javax.inject.Named;\n     8→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.BookingServiceFacade;\n     9→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.dto.CargoRoute;\n    10→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.dto.RouteCandidate;\n    11→\n    12→/**\n    13→ * Handles itinerary selection. Operates against a dedicated service facade, and could easily be\n    14→ * rewritten as a thick Swing client. Completely separated from the domain layer, unlike the\n    15→ * tracking user interface.\n    16→ *\n    17→ * <p>In order to successfully keep the domain model shielded from user interface considerations,\n    18→ * this approach is generally preferred to the one taken in the tracking controller. However, there\n    19→ * is never any one perfect solution for all situations, so we've chosen to demonstrate two\n    20→ * polarized ways to build user interfaces.\n    21→ */\n    22→@Named\n    23→@ViewScoped\n    24→public class ItinerarySelection implements Serializable {\n    25→\n    26→  private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;\n    27→\n    28→  @Inject private BookingServiceFacade bookingServiceFacade;\n    29→\n    30→  List<RouteCandidate> routeCandidates;\n    31→  private String trackingId;\n    32→  private CargoRoute cargo;\n    33→\n    34→  public List<RouteCandidate> getRouteCandidates() {\n    35→    return routeCandidates;\n    36→  }\n    37→\n    38→  public String getTrackingId() {\n    39→    return trackingId;\n    40→  }\n    41→\n    42→  public void setTrackingId(String trackingId) {\n    43→    this.trackingId = trackingId;\n    44→  }\n    45→\n    46→  public CargoRoute getCargo() {\n    47→    return cargo;\n    48→  }\n    49→\n    50→  public List<RouteCandidate> getRouteCanditates() {\n    51→    return routeCandidates;\n    52→  }\n    53→\n    54→  public void load() {\n    55→    cargo = bookingServiceFacade.loadCargoForRouting(trackingId);\n    56→    routeCandidates = bookingServiceFacade.requestPossibleRoutesForCargo(trackingId);\n    57→  }\n    58→\n    59→  public String assignItinerary(int routeIndex) {\n    60→    RouteCandidate route = routeCandidates.get(routeIndex);\n    61→    bookingServiceFacade.assignCargoToRoute(trackingId, route);\n    62→\n    63→    return \"show.html?faces-redirect=true&trackingId=\" + trackingId;\n    64→  }\n    65→}\n    66→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01P9o4BPvGfqGgpY4qAiCPkX","session_id":"cb64f649-59c6-4f3a-a73b-f24ff02d923c","uuid":"49d19554-be56-4c64-9cda-628d76bf5c1f"}
